# üìò GIT WORKFLOW ‚Äì DETAILED NOTES (UP TO BRANCHES)

---

## 1Ô∏è‚É£ What is Git?

Git is a **distributed version control system** used to:

* Track code changes
* Collaborate with teams
* Maintain history
* Work on multiple features using branches

---

## 2Ô∏è‚É£ Git Architecture (Very Important)

### Git has 4 main areas:

```
Working Directory ‚Üí Staging Area ‚Üí Local Repository ‚Üí Remote Repository
```

### Explanation:

* **Working Directory**: Where you edit files
* **Staging Area**: Where changes are prepared for commit
* **Local Repository**: Where commits are stored locally
* **Remote Repository**: Central repo (GitHub, GitLab)

---

## 3Ô∏è‚É£ Initial Git Setup (One-time)

```bash
git config --global user.name "BadamTeja"
git config --global user.email "tejabadam810@gmail.com"
```

Check config:

```bash
git config --list
```

---

## 4Ô∏è‚É£ Creating or Getting a Repository

### Initialize a new repository

```bash
git init
```

Creates a hidden `.git` folder.

---

### Clone an existing repository

```bash
git clone <repo_url>
```

Example:

```bash
git clone git@github.com:BadamTeja/devopspractice.git
```

---

## 5Ô∏è‚É£ Daily Git Workflow (Core Concept)

### Step 1: Check status

```bash
git status
```

Shows:

* Modified files
* Untracked files
* Staged files

---

### Step 2: Add files to staging

```bash
git add file.txt
git add .
```

Purpose:

* Moves changes from working directory ‚Üí staging area

---

### Step 3: Commit changes

```bash
git commit -m "Meaningful commit message"
```

Purpose:

* Saves snapshot into local repository

---

### Step 4: Push changes to remote

```bash
git push origin main
```

Purpose:

* Sends commits to GitHub

---

## 6Ô∏è‚É£ Understanding Git Internals (Interview)

```
Edit file
   ‚Üì
git add
   ‚Üì
git commit
   ‚Üì
git push
```

OR

```
Working Dir ‚Üí Staging ‚Üí Local Repo ‚Üí Remote Repo
```

---

## 7Ô∏è‚É£ Viewing History

### View commits

```bash
git log
```

Exit log:

```text
Press q
```

### Compact view

```bash
git log --oneline
```

---

## 8Ô∏è‚É£ Branches ‚Äì Introduction

### What is a branch?

* A branch is a **parallel version of code**
* Used to develop features without affecting main code

Default branch:

```text
main (or master)
```

---

## 9Ô∏è‚É£ Branch Commands (Detailed)

### Check current branch

```bash
git branch
```

---

### Create a new branch

```bash
git branch feature-login
```

Branch created but not switched.

---

### Switch to branch

```bash
git checkout feature-login
```

---

### Create & switch (shortcut)

```bash
git checkout -b feature-login
```

---

## üîü Working on a Branch

```bash
git add .
git commit -m "Added login feature"
```

Commits stay only in that branch.

---

## 1Ô∏è‚É£1Ô∏è‚É£ Push Branch to GitHub

```bash
git push origin feature-login
```

Now branch appears on GitHub.

---

## 1Ô∏è‚É£2Ô∏è‚É£ Merge Branch into Main

```bash
git checkout main
git merge feature-login
```

Then push:

```bash
git push origin main
```

---

## 1Ô∏è‚É£3Ô∏è‚É£ Delete Branch (After Merge)

### Local branch delete

```bash
git branch -d feature-login
```

### Remote branch delete

```bash
git push origin --delete feature-login
```

---

